Installation Instructions
=========================

Prerequisites
-------------
- Linux x86_64 with an NVIDIA GPU (Compute Capability >= 1.0)
- CUDA Toolkit (11.0 or later recommended), which includes the NPP libraries
- g++ with C++11 support

Environment Setup
-----------------
1. Install the CUDA Toolkit from https://developer.nvidia.com/cuda-downloads

2. Ensure the CUDA binaries are on your PATH:
     export PATH=/usr/local/cuda/bin:$PATH
     export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/usr/local/cuda/lib64:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH

   If CUDA is installed to a non-default location, set CUDA_PATH:
     export CUDA_PATH=/path/to/cuda

3. The required CUDA Samples helper headers (helper_cuda.h, helper_string.h)
   and NPP utility headers (Exceptions.h, ImageIO.h, ImagesCPU.h, ImagesNPP.h)
   are included in the include/ directory. If you prefer to use headers from an
   external cuda-samples installation, set:
     export CUDA_SAMPLES_PATH=/path/to/cuda-samples

Building
--------
    make

   This produces bin/imageRotationNPP.

   To clean build artifacts:
    make clean

Data Preparation
----------------
The input image must be in PGM (Portable Gray Map) format. A sample Lena.pgm
is provided in data/. If you only have Lena.png, convert it:

    python3 -c "from PIL import Image; Image.open('data/Lena.png').convert('L').save('data/Lena.pgm')"

    or with ImageMagick:

    convert data/Lena.png -colorspace Gray data/Lena.pgm

Running
-------
    ./run.sh

    or manually:

    ./bin/imageRotationNPP --input data/Lena.pgm

The rotated output is saved as Lena_rotate.pgm in the current directory.
